century urban black health care by showing a program that was simultaneously racialized and cutting-edge. It reveals that even the most well-meaning public health programs may inadvertently reinforce perceptions of inferiority that they were created to fix.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxHealthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxHealthzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aMaternal health servicesxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aMaternal health serviceszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aMinoritiesxHealthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aMinoritiesxHealthzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aPovertyxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPovertyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban healthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aUrban healthzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aUrban healthzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aWomen's health servicesxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aWomen's health serviceszNew York (State)zNew York. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479875184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479875184.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK